Measurements. Cephalothorax: length 1.5-1.7, width 1.9-2.0, height 0.6. Eye field: length 0.8-1.0, anterior width 1.3-1.5, posterior width 1.9-2.0. Abdomen: length 2.4-2.9, width 2.8-3.2.
</paragraph>
<caption id="3011DBC07629B3A8FBDF4210BE4846F1" doi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures104-109" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427071" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" start="Figures 104–109" startId="F20">
<paragraph id="F1DF8812A6EDF661573A7A786024B680" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="DF4F1A3662F841378DB2B1E155BA54B9" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Figures 104-109.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="03CB76285D3D55B6AE6511D0C85BE6DD" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Pachyballus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pachyballus transversus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transversus">
<emphasis id="B749B15773FD325C9566649A9F42DA6A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Pachyballus transversus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, female 
<emphasis id="17E4F84F05A6A1768F6C61D4455A9485" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">104-106</emphasis>
habitus, dorsal view 
<emphasis id="71FEB1B494FCDEDB5F7D472F2DE0D2E8" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">107-109</emphasis>
epigyne (dissected from specimens visible above) (
<emphasis id="2DC3F16CE30AAFA82D438CE3E323ED5B" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">104, 106</emphasis>
specimens from Congo 
<emphasis id="CB31AEF89DEDC03F4D4A9B2742220658" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">105</emphasis>
specimen from Ethiopia).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="4F4225C1CE2A0196D43C927D0C83CD28" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
General appearance as in Figs 
<figureCitation id="3884C1B89E709E36FE7D39C7F45EAB3B" captionStart="Figures 98–103" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figures 98 - 103. Pachyballus transversus, male 98 habitus, ventral view 99 - 102 habitus, dorsal view, 103 palpal organ, ventral view (all specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures98-103" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427070" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">98-102</figureCitation>
. Slightly larger than 
<taxonomicName id="82D8029B3F85A454FD1D212D745A7821" genus="P." lsidName="P. flavipes" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis id="4E7B6AFB7E98449D596F58ECA934DAC7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">P. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, body flattened, covered with hard integument, pitted. Carapace wide, dark brown to blackish, vicinity of eyes black. Eye field strongly trapezoid, more than in other 
<taxonomicName id="EE44806B65FED6A78EC028999A0E6909" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Pachyballus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pachyballus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9DD871401846948EB87543FEF222BFAD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Pachyballus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. Its width at last row of eyes is a quarter larger than its anterior width. A few hairs and long bristles at anterior eyes. Clypeus low. Chelicerae with short fang, three small teeth on promargin and four teeth with fused base on retromargin (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C10F21471886F445703D50368C55114C" captionStart="Figures 110–116" captionStartId="F21" captionText="Figures 110 - 116. Pachyballus transversus 110 cheliceral dentition 111 palpal organ, ventral view 112 palpal organ, lateral view 113 - 116 epigyne (114 specimen from Ethiopia 115 specimen from Somalia 113, 116 specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures110-116" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427072" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">110</figureCitation>
). Mouth parts brown, sternum oval, dark. Abdomen heart-shaped, wide, clearly wider than long. Colouration of abdomen usually light, orange brownish with blackish edge, sometimes yellowish or brown. Sigilla clearly visible. Venter brown, with typical scuta (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4B099FB45051127E1D4D17F5C59BB2D2" captionStart="Figures 98–103" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figures 98 - 103. Pachyballus transversus, male 98 habitus, ventral view 99 - 102 habitus, dorsal view, 103 palpal organ, ventral view (all specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures98-103" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427070" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">98</figureCitation>
). First pair of legs brown, slightly larger than other pairs, with femora and tibiae thickened, tibiae slightly flattened dorsally. All legs brownish with lighter tarsi. Palps dark, structure as in Figs 
<figureCitation id="A3A5D42BCED7CE32383712FD8AB5A2EC" captionStart="Figures 98–103" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figures 98 - 103. Pachyballus transversus, male 98 habitus, ventral view 99 - 102 habitus, dorsal view, 103 palpal organ, ventral view (all specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures98-103" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427070" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">103</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="7F2E17926BC4473F90FA56933CB5DBEC" captionStart="Figures 110–116" captionStartId="F21" captionText="Figures 110 - 116. Pachyballus transversus 110 cheliceral dentition 111 palpal organ, ventral view 112 palpal organ, lateral view 113 - 116 epigyne (114 specimen from Ethiopia 115 specimen from Somalia 113, 116 specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures110-116" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427072" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">111</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="E70BAA6DB1DF0052397DD60BCBA0F82D" captionStart="Figures 110–116" captionStartId="F21" captionText="Figures 110 - 116. Pachyballus transversus 110 cheliceral dentition 111 palpal organ, ventral view 112 palpal organ, lateral view 113 - 116 epigyne (114 specimen from Ethiopia 115 specimen from Somalia 113, 116 specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures110-116" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427072" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">112</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="61B275EA1C2168B264DF689E0D5490CA" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="C32E7A674D2A08EFA165C6D144EAF0BC" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Female.</emphasis>
Measurements. Cephalothorax: length 1.4-1.6, width 1.6-2.0, height 0.7. Eye field: length 0.7-0.8, anterior width 1.2-1.5, posterior width 1.8-2.0. Abdomen: length 2.4-2.9, width 2.8-3.2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="059360BEE0FDA4F82800B7E54EF6B70B" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
General appearance as in Figs 
<figureCitation id="5A013BE1CC309889A19B83FC2E9BD921" captionStart="Figures 104–109" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figures 104 - 109. Pachyballus transversus, female 104 - 106 habitus, dorsal view 107 - 109 epigyne (dissected from specimens visible above) (104, 106 specimens from Congo 105 specimen from Ethiopia)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures104-109" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427071" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">104-106</figureCitation>
. Similar to male, eye field strongly trapezoid. Abdomen wide, rounded, with visible sigilla. All legs yellow, sometimes femora, patellae and tibiae brownish. Palps dark. Epigyne typical, with horseshoe-shaped anterior depression (Figs 
<figureCitation id="5C00E8A5B6EFAD15CFBAE3EAA659D47D" captionStart="Figures 104–109" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figures 104 - 109. Pachyballus transversus, female 104 - 106 habitus, dorsal view 107 - 109 epigyne (dissected from specimens visible above) (104, 106 specimens from Congo 105 specimen from Ethiopia)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures104-109" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427071" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">107-109</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="F268A1C86596AA81FB1013E41EF5C54A" captionStart="Figures 110–116" captionStartId="F21" captionText="Figures 110 - 116. Pachyballus transversus 110 cheliceral dentition 111 palpal organ, ventral view 112 palpal organ, lateral view 113 - 116 epigyne (114 specimen from Ethiopia 115 specimen from Somalia 113, 116 specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures110-116" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427072" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">113-116</figureCitation>
). Copulatory ducts long, forming several loops, spermathecae strongly sclerotised (Figs 
<figureCitation id="F20F4E7F0BA5EE68E81D62755DFB8598" captionStart="Figures 117–122" captionStartId="F22" captionText="Figures 117 - 122. Pachyballus transversus, internal structure of epigyne 117 - 120 ventral view 121, 122 dorsal view (117 specimen from Ethiopia 118 specimen from Somalia, other specimens from Congo)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures117-122" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427073" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">118-122</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="07F9CA28596367AD56F8917E74AAEF40" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="C9C7E3EC2F756E98C0D0A320DF4ED8A9" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Immature specimens.</emphasis>
Shape of body as in adults, abdomen with two oval scuta, close to each other on dorsum (Figs 
<figureCitation id="0C911D65272A13D11AD638CF04536B01" captionStart="Figures 189–192" captionStartId="F35" captionText="Figures 189 - 192. Dorsal scuta of abdomen, immature specimens. 189, 190 Peplometus biscutellatus 191, 192 Pachyballus transversus 189, 191 younger instar 190, 192 subadult." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures189-192" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427087" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">191</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="CB803F928961AAD9E38C7EF721A3FE9B" captionStart="Figures 189–192" captionStartId="F35" captionText="Figures 189 - 192. Dorsal scuta of abdomen, immature specimens. 189, 190 Peplometus biscutellatus 191, 192 Pachyballus transversus 189, 191 younger instar 190, 192 subadult." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures189-192" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427087" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">192</figureCitation>
). Ventral scuta absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
